# Testing JavaScript: A Practical Guide to TDD with Jest (2026)

*Testing isn't optional. It's the difference between "I think it works" and "I know it works."*

## Why Testing Gets Pushed Aside (And Why It Shouldn't)

```
Common excuses:
→ "I don't have time to write tests" → You'll spend MORE time debugging
→ "My code is too simple to test" → Until it's not
→ "Tests break when I refactor" → Good! They catch your mistakes
→ "I don't know how" → That's what this guide is for

The truth:
Tests are documentation that never lies.
Tests are safety nets for refactoring.
Tests are confidence boosters for deployments.
```

## Setup

```bash
# Jest is the standard for JavaScript testing
npm install --save-dev jest @types/jest

# For Node.js ESM (package.json has "type": "module"):
# npm install --save-dev jest@beta  # Or use node:test built-in!

# package.json scripts:
{
  "scripts": {
    "test": "jest",
    "test:watch": "jest --watch",
    "test:coverage": "jest --coverage",
    "test:verbose": "jest --verbose"
  }
}
```

## The Basics: Your First Test

```javascript
// math.js — code we want to test
export function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

export function multiply(a, b) {
  return a * b;
}

export function divide(a, b) {
  if (b === 0) throw new Error('Division by zero');
  return a / b;
}

// math.test.js — tests go in same folder or __tests__/ directory
import { add, multiply, divide } from './math.js';

describe('Math utilities', () => {

  test('add() adds two numbers', () => {
    expect(add(2, 3)).toBe(5);
    expect(add(-1, 1)).toBe(0);
    expect(add(0.1, 0.2)).toBeCloseTo(0.3); // Floating point!
  });

  test('multiply() multiplies two numbers', () => {
    expect(multiply(3, 4)).toBe(12);
    expect(multiply(-2, 5)).toBe(-10);
    expect(multiply(0, 100)).toBe(0);
  });

  test('divide() divides correctly', () => {
    expect(divide(10, 2)).toBe(5);
    expect(divide(7, 2)).toBe(3.5);
  });

  test('divide() throws on zero divisor', () => {
    expect(() => divide(10, 0)).toThrow('Division by zero');
  });
});
```

## The Test Anatomy

```javascript
// Every test follows this pattern:

test('description of expected behavior', () => {
  // 1. ARRANGE — Set up the test data
  const input = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5];

  // 2 ACT — Call the function being tested
  const result = calculateAverage(input);

  // 3 ASSERT — Verify the result
  expect(result).toBeCloseTo(2.8);
});

// describe() groups related tests (creates a test suite)
describe('User service', () => {
  beforeEach(() => { /* Runs before EACH test in this group */ });
  afterEach(() => { /* Cleanup after each test */ });
  beforeAll(() => { /* Runs once before all tests */ });
  afterAll(() => { /* Runs once after all tests */ });
});
```

## Matchers You'll Use Every Day

```javascript
// Equality
expect(value).toBe(42);              // Strict equality (===)
expect(value).toEqual({ a: 1 });     // Deep equality (objects/arrays)
expect(value).toStrictEqual({ a: 1 }); // Deep + strict (no extra properties)

// Truthiness
expect(value).toBeTruthy();          // Falsy check inverse
expect(value).toBeFalsy();
expect(value).toBeDefined();
expect(value).toBeNull();
expect(value).toBeUndefined();        // Not null AND not undefined
expect(value).toBeNaN();

// Numbers
expect(count).toBeGreaterThan(0);
expect(count).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(10);
expect(ratio).toBeLessThan(1);
expect(price).toBeCloseTo(9.99, 2);   // Within 2 decimal places

// Strings
expect(name).toMatch(/alice/i);      // Regex match
expect(url).toContain('https://');
expect(error.message).toContain('invalid');
expect(str).toHaveLength(10);

// Arrays
expect(items).toContain('apple');     // Value exists in array
expect(ids).toEqual(expect.arrayContaining([1, 2])); // Contains subset
expect(arr).toHaveLength(5);

// Objects
expect(user).toHaveProperty('name', 'Alice');
expect(obj).toMatchObject({ a: 1, b: expect.any(Number) });

// Exceptions
expect(fn).toThrow();               // Throws anything
expect(fn).toThrow(Error);           // Throws specific type
expect(fn).toThrow('specific message'); // Message matches
expect(asyncFn()).rejects.toThrow();  // Promise rejects

// Promises
await expect(promise).resolves.toBe(value);
await expect(promise).rejects.toThrow('error');

// Custom matchers (create reusable assertions)
expect.extend({
  toBeWithinRange(received, floor, ceiling) {
    const pass = received >= floor && received <= ceiling;
    return {
      pass,
      message: () =>
        `expected ${received} to be within range ${floor}-${ceiling}`,
    };
  }
});

expect(42).toBeWithinRange(40, 50); // Custom matcher!
```

## Testing Async Code

```javascript
// Option 1: async/await (cleanest!)
test('fetchUser returns user data', async () => {
  const user = await userService.findById('usr_123');
  expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
});

// Option 2: Promises (.then/.catch)
test('fetchUser returns user data', () => {
  return userService.findById('usr_123').then(user => {
    expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
  });
  // MUST return the promise so Jest waits!
});

// Option 3: Callbacks (legacy)
test('callback receives data', (done) => {
  fetchData((err, data) => {
    expect(err).toBeNull();
    expect(data).toBeDefined();
    done(); // Tell Jest callback is complete
  });
});

// Testing error cases
test('throws when user not found', async () => {
  await expect(userService.findById('nonexistent'))
    .rejects.toThrow('User not found');
});

// Testing timeouts
test('responds within timeout', async () => {
  const start = Date.now();
  await fetchData();
  const elapsed = Date.now() - start;
  expect(elapsed).toBeLessThan(5000); // Under 5 seconds
}, 10000); // Test-level timeout override (default 5s)

// Retry flaky tests
test('flaky network call', async () => {
  let result;
  for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    try {
      result = await unstableApiCall();
      break;
    } catch {}
  }
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
});
```

## Mocking: When You Need to Isolate

```javascript
// Why mock?
// → Remove external dependencies (database, API, filesystem)
// → Make tests fast (no real HTTP calls)
// → Simulate edge cases (network errors, timeouts)
// → Control unpredictable behavior (random numbers, dates)

// --- Manual mocks ---
const mockDb = {
  users: [{ id: '1', name: 'Alice' }],
  find(id) { return this.users.find(u => u.id === id) || null; },
};

// Replace real DB with mock in test
jest.mock('./database.js', () => mockDb);

// --- jest.mock() ---
// Automatically mocks all functions in a module
jest.mock('./apiClient.js');
import api from './apiClient.js';

test('calls API with correct params', () => {
  api.getUsers.mockResolvedValue([{ id: 1 }]); // Setup mock return

  const users = await fetchUsers();

  expect(api.getUsers).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/users');
  expect(users).toEqual([{ id: 1 }]);
});

// --- jest.fn() ---
const callback = jest.fn();
callback('hello', 42);

expect(callback).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(callback).toHaveBeenCalledWith('hello', 42);
expect(callback).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
expect(callback.mock.calls[0]).toEqual(['hello', 42]);
expect(callback.mock.results[0].value.toBe(undefined));

// Return values
const mockFetch = jest.fn()
  .mockResolvedValueOnce({ data: [] })       // First call
  .mockRejectedValueOnce(new Error('fail'))   // Second call
  .mockResolvedValueOnce({ data: [1, 2] });    // Third call

// --- Spying on real methods ---
const realService = new UserService();
const spy = jest.spyOn(realService, 'findById');
spy.mockResolvedValue(mockUser);

const user = await realService.findById('123');
expect(spy).toHaveBeenCalledWith('123');

spy.mockRestore(); // Always restore after spying!

// --- Timer mocks ---
test('debounce works correctly', () => {
  jest.useFakeTimers();

  const fn = jest.fn();
  const debounced = debounce(fn, 1000);

  debounced(); // Call at t=0
  debounced(); // Call again at t=0 (should reset timer)

  jest.advanceTimersByTime(999);
  expect(fn).not.toHaveBeenCalled(); // Not yet!

  jest.advanceTimersByTime(1);
  expect(fn).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1); // Now called once

  jest.useRealTimers(); // Always restore!
});
```

## Testing Express APIs

```javascript
// app.test.js
import request from 'supertest';
import express from 'express';
import userRouter from '../src/routes/users.js';

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
app.use('/api/users', userRouter);

describe('GET /api/users/:id', () => {
  test('returns 200 with user data for valid ID', async () => {
    const res = await request(app)
      .get('/api/users/usr_123')
      .set('Accept', 'application/json');

    expect(res.status).toBe(200);
    expect(res.body.success).toBe(true);
    expect(res.body.data.id).toBe('usr_123');
    expect(res.body.data.email).toBeDefined();
  });

  test('returns 404 for non-existent user', async () => {
    const res = await request(app)
      .get('/api/users/nonexistent');

    expect(res.status).toBe(404);
    expect(res.body.error.code).toBe('NOT_FOUND');
  });

  test('returns 400 for invalid ID format', async () => {
    const res = await request(app)
      .get('/api/users/not-a-valid-id');

    expect(res.status).toBe(400);
    expect(res.body.error.code).toBe('VALIDATION_ERROR');
  });

  test('POST creates user with valid data', async () => {
    const res = await request(app)
      .post('/api/users')
      .send({ email: 'new@example.com', name: 'New User', password: 'SecurePass123!' })
      .set('Accept', 'application/json');

    expect(res.status).toBe(201);
    expect(res.body.data.id).toBeDefined();
    expect(res.body.data.email).toBe('new@example.com');
  });

  test('POST rejects duplicate email', async () => {
    // First create succeeds
    await request(app)
      .post('/api/users')
      .send({ email: 'dup@test.com', name: 'User1', password: 'Pass123!' });

    // Second create fails
    const res = await request(app)
      .post('/api/users')
      .send({ email: 'dup@test.com', name: 'User2', password: 'Pass123!' });

    expect(res.status).toBe(409);
    expect(res.body.error.code).toBe('CONFLICT');
  });
});
```

## TDD: Test-Driven Development Workflow

```
RED → GREEN → REFACTOR

1. RED: Write a failing test for the feature you need
2. GREEN: Write MINIMUM code to make the test pass
3. REFACTOR: Improve the code while keeping tests green
4. Repeat

The discipline: Don't write production code without a failing test first.
```

### TDD Example: Building a Price Calculator

```javascript
// Step 1: RED — Write the test FIRST
describe('PriceCalculator', () => {
  test('calculates base price', () => {
    const calc = new PriceCalculator(100);
    expect(calc.subtotal()).toBe(100);
  });

  test('applies tax rate', () => {
    const calc = new PriceCalculator(100);
    calc.setTaxRate(0.08); // 8%
    expect(calc.tax()).toBe(8);
    expect(calc.total()).toBe(108);
  });

  test('applies discount percentage', () => {
    const calc = new PriceCalculator(100);
    calc.setDiscount(0.15); // 15% off
    expect(calc.discountAmount()).toBe(15);
    expect(calc.subtotal()).toBe(85);
  });

  test('discount applies before tax', () => {
    const calc = new PriceCalculator(100);
    calc.setDiscount(0.10); // 10% off → $90
    calc.setTaxRate(0.08);  // 8% tax on $90 → $97.20
    expect(calc.total()).toBeCloseTo(97.2);
  });

  test('throws for negative price', () => {
    expect(() => new PriceCalculator(-50)).toThrow('Price must be positive');
  });

  test('throws for discount > 100%', () => {
    const calc = new PriceCalculator(100);
    expect(() => calc.setDiscount(1.5)).toThrow('Discount cannot exceed 100%');
  });
});

// Step 2: GREEN — Minimal implementation
class PriceCalculator {
  constructor(price) {
    if (price <= 0) throw new Error('Price must be positive');
    this._originalPrice = price;
    this._discount = 0;
    this._taxRate = 0;
  }

  subtotal() {
    return this._originalPrice * (1 - this._discount);
  }

  setDiscount(rate) {
    if (rate < 0 || rate > 1) throw new Error('Discount cannot exceed 100%');
    this._discount = rate;
  }

  setTaxRate(rate) {
    this._taxRate = rate;
  }

  discountAmount() {
    return this._originalPrice * this._discount;
  }

  tax() {
    return this.subtotal() * this._taxRate;
  }

  total() {
    return this.subtotal() + this.tax();
  }
}

// Step 3: REFACTOR — Improve now that tests have your back
// Maybe extract validation into a shared utility?
// Maybe add currency rounding logic?
// Tests confirm nothing breaks during refactoring.
```

## Coverage: What Actually Matters

```bash
# Run with coverage report
npm run test:coverage

# Output shows:
# % Branches | Lines | Functions | Statements
# ----------------|-------|-----------|----------
#      85%    |  92%  |    90%    |    91%

# jest.config.js
module.exports = {
  coverageProvider: 'v8',           // Built-in coverage (no Istanbul needed!)
  collectCoverageFrom: [
    'src/**/*.js',
    '!src/**/*.test.js',
    '!src/config/**',
    '!src/index.js',              // Entry point usually doesn't need coverage
  ],
  coverageThreshold: {
    global: {
      branches: 80,
      functions: 90,
      lines: 90,
      statements: 90,
    },
  },  // Fails CI if below threshold!
  coverageReporters: ['text', 'lcov', 'html'],
};
```

**Coverage goals by project type:**
- Library/package you publish: **90%+** (users depend on it)
- Internal tooling: **70-80%** (pragmatic balance)
- Quick prototype: **any coverage > none**

**What coverage DOESN'T tell you:**
- Are you testing the RIGHT things? (100% coverage of wrong code = useless)
- Edge cases handled? (happy path only = false confidence)
- Integration issues? (unit tests don't catch these)

## Testing Best Practices

```
DO:
✅ One assertion per test (when practical)
✅ Descriptive test names that read like requirements
✅ Test behavior, not implementation
✅ Use constants for test data (easy to update)
✅ Each test independent (no shared state between tests)
✅ Test edge cases: empty input, null, huge data, unicode

DON'T:
❌ Test getters/setters (trivial code doesn't need tests)
❌ Test implementation details (refactoring shouldn't break tests)
❌ Share mutable state between tests (causes flaky order-dependent failures)
❌ Ignore flaky tests (they hide real problems)
❌ Over-mock (if everything is mocked, you're testing mocks, not code)
❌ Sleep/delay in tests (use fake timers instead)

Test naming convention:
✅ 'should return 404 when user does not exist'
✅ 'calculates total with discount applied before tax'
❌ 'test user' (too vague)
❌ 'user test 1' (meaningless)
```

---

*Do you write tests before or after code? Team TDD or pragmatic after-the-fact?*

